<h2>Why Convert a PDF to Grayscale?</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Reduce printing costs:</strong> Colour printing costs 2–5× more per page than black-and-white. Converting to grayscale before printing saves significant money, especially for long documents.</li>
  <li><strong>Printer compatibility:</strong> Some printers are black-and-white only. A grayscale PDF prints cleanly on monochrome printers without colour-to-grayscale translation artefacts.</li>
  <li><strong>Archiving:</strong> Grayscale archives are smaller, more consistent, and render identically across all devices regardless of colour display settings.</li>
  <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Some readers have colour vision deficiencies. A well-designed grayscale document is easier to read than a colour document that relies on colour to convey meaning.</li>
  <li><strong>Professional appearance:</strong> Some formal or legal documents are expected to be black and white.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Convert PDF to Grayscale in Adobe Acrobat</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Adobe Acrobat Pro.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Tools → Print Production → Convert Colors</strong>.</li>
  <li>Set the "Conversion Space" to "Gray Gamma 2.2" (or another grayscale profile).</li>
  <li>Set "Document Colors" to include all colour spaces.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>OK</strong> and save.</li>
</ol>

<p>Note: Adobe Acrobat Pro is a paid application. The PDFWonder browser tool above is free.</p>

<h2>How to Print a Colour PDF in Black and White (Without Converting the File)</h2>

<p>If you only need grayscale for printing (not to save a grayscale file), you can set your printer to black-and-white mode without converting the PDF:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Open print dialog → Printer Properties → look for "Color Mode" or "Grayscale" option → select Black &amp; White → print.</li>
  <li><strong>Mac:</strong> Open print dialog → click "Show Details" → Colour/Quality settings → select "Black &amp; White" or "Grayscale".</li>
  <li><strong>Specific printers:</strong> Most HP, Canon, and Epson printers have a grayscale print option in their advanced settings.</li>
</ul>

<p>This does not create a grayscale PDF — it only prints in grayscale. Use the browser tool to create a grayscale PDF file.</p>

<h2>Grayscale vs. Compressing a PDF — Not the Same Thing</h2>

<p>
  Converting to grayscale removes colour but does not necessarily reduce file size. To reduce file size, use the <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-compress">PDF Compressor</a>. For the best result on a large colour PDF: convert to grayscale first, then run through the compressor.
</p>

